or gender equality. Greenburg critically interrogates a new imperial feminism and its central role securing US hegemony. Women's incorporation into combat through emotional labor has reinforced gender stereotypes, with counterinsurgency framing female soldiers as global ambassadors for women's rights. This book provides an analysis of US imperialism that keeps the present in tension with the past, clarifying where colonial ideologies of race, gender, and sexuality have resurfaced and how they are changing today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aAfghan War, 2001-2021xParticipation, Female. 0aCounterinsurgencyzAfghanistanxHistoryy21st century. 0aCounterinsurgencyzIraqxHistoryy21st century. 0aImperialismxSocial aspects. 0aIraq War, 2003-2011xParticipation, Female. 0aSex rolezUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aWomen soldiersxGovernment policyzUnited States. 4aANTHROPOLOGY. 4aGENDER STUDIES. 4aGEOGRAPHY. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh  afemale engagement teams, post 9/11 wars, gender and war, female counterinsurgency teams, female soldiers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501767753?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501767753423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501767753/original  a978-3-11-075183-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK